<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900503-0074</DOCNO><DOCID>900503-0074.</DOCID><HL>   Republic Health   Leaves Chapter 11   As Public Company</HL><DATE>05/03/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13</SO><CO>   REPHV</CO><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   DALLAS -- Republic Health Corp. said it completedreorganization under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Codeand emerged as a publicly traded company.   The owner of 14 acute-care hospitals and two psychiatrichospitals went private in August 1986 in a $406.2 millionleveraged buy-out led by Donaldson, Lufkin andamp; JenretteSecurities Corp. But changes in Medicare regulations andoverly optimistic projections made the debt burden too heavy.The company and its parent, REPH Acquisition Co., soughtbankruptcy-court protection last December to restructuretotal debt of about $645 million.</LP><TEXT>   Under the reorganization plan, which was approved by themajority of the company's creditors before the company filedfor Chapter 11 protection, Republic Health and its parentreduced total debt to $379 million and reduced their annualinterest obligations to $40 million, from $89 million.   Of the remaining debt, $74 million is owed banks and $86million is owed under capitalized leases and notes. Theremainder consists of new securities issued to creditors, thecompany said.   As part of the reorganization, REPH Acquisition was mergedinto the now-publicly traded Republic Health. Debtholders own88.8% of the new stock; holders of the old preferred stockown 6.1%; and holders of the old common stock own 5.1%.   Under the reorganization plan, the company said, secureddebtholders received 81 cents for each dollar owed; seniorsubordinated debtholders received 67 cents; and subordinateddebtholders received 20 cents.</TEXT></DOC>